  "signature": "ed25519:b1d4f7a2c9e3b6d8f1a4c7e2b5d9f3a6c1e8b4d7f2a5c9e1b6d3f8a2c5e7b4d1",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "At MRL 5 for a Class III device, software quality assurance requires Gradation 4: full version control, automated regression testing, independent code review, and documented change management. The CFD solver (OpenFOAM 9) is version-controlled and has documented release notes, but automated regression testing covers only 38% of hemolysis-relevant code paths. Independent code review was not performed for the custom hemolysis power-law UDF. Change management documentation is incomplete for three solver modifications made during the study. Achieved level 2 reflects documented version control and basic unit testing only.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/sqa-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA acceptance criteria for MRL 5 Class III device",
        "description": "Required: full version control with tagged releases, automated regression test suite covering ≥90% of hemolysis-relevant code paths, independent third-party code review of all custom UDFs, and documented change management for all solver modifications. All four criteria must be met to achieve Gradation 4."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Numerical code verification at MRL 5 requires Gradation 4: method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the full coupled Navier-Stokes and hemolysis transport system, with order-of-accuracy confirmation for all governing equations. MMS was applied to the Navier-Stokes solver and confirmed second-order spatial accuracy. However, MMS was not applied to the hemolysis power-law transport equation or the red blood cell damage accumulation model. Benchmark comparisons against three analytical solutions were completed for laminar flow cases. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects MMS for fluid equations only, without extension to hemolysis sub-model.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/code-verification-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Code verification acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: MMS applied to all governing equations including hemolysis transport and RBC damage accumulation models, with confirmed spatial and temporal order of accuracy. Benchmark comparisons against analytical solutions for at least 5 canonical cases spanning the relevant Reynolds number range."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Discretization error quantification at MRL 5 requires Gradation 4: systematic Richardson extrapolation on three or more geometrically similar meshes with GCI < 2% for all quantities of interest, including wall shear stress relevant to hemolysis. The mesh convergence study achieved GCI < 3% for velocity magnitude (marginal) but GCI of 7.2% for wall shear stress, which directly drives hemolysis index predictions. The 32M cell mesh was computationally prohibitive for full Monte Carlo UQ runs, so UQ was performed on the 8M cell mesh with acknowledged discretization uncertainty. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects systematic convergence study with GCI reported but not meeting the < 2% threshold for hemolysis-relevant quantities.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/discretization-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: Richardson extrapolation on ≥3 geometrically similar meshes; GCI < 2% for velocity magnitude, wall shear stress, and hemolysis index at all 5 operating points. UQ must be performed on the mesh achieving GCI < 2% for hemolysis-relevant quantities."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "At MRL 5, test conditions must achieve Gradation 5: experimental conditions match COU operating conditions with full characterization of all boundary condition uncertainties, including blood rheology, inlet velocity profiles, and temperature. The benchtop validation used porcine blood (confirmatory) and ASTM F1841 glycerol-saline analogue (primary). Inlet velocity profiles were assumed uniform (plug flow) rather than measured with PIV. Temperature was controlled to 37±1°C but not continuously monitored. Blood analogue viscosity was measured at a single shear rate rather than characterized across the full shear-rate range relevant to the pump. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects controlled temperature and measured bulk viscosity without full rheological characterization or measured inlet profiles.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-conditions-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: PIV-measured inlet velocity profiles used as CFD boundary conditions; full rheological characterization of blood analogue across shear rates 1–10000 s⁻¹; continuous temperature monitoring ±0.5°C; all boundary condition uncertainties propagated into validation comparison. Porcine blood used as primary (not confirmatory) validation fluid."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Output comparison at MRL 5 requires Gradation 5: quantitative validation metrics with uncertainty bounds on both simulation and experiment, statistical hypothesis testing, and comparison of spatial field quantities (not just scalar hemolysis index). Validation was performed by comparing scalar NIH values at 5 operating points; no spatial field comparison (e.g., velocity fields, shear stress distributions) was performed against experimental PIV data. Experimental measurement uncertainty was estimated from literature rather than characterized in situ. No formal hypothesis test (e.g., ASME V&V 20 validation metric) was applied. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects quantitative scalar comparison with literature-derived experimental uncertainty.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/output-comparison-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: ASME V&V 20 validation metric computed with in-situ experimental uncertainty characterization; spatial field comparison of velocity and shear stress against PIV measurements; statistical equivalence testing at 95% confidence for all 5 operating points; comparison of hemolysis index distributions (not only mean values)."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "rationale": "The quantities of interest (NIH hemolysis index, wall shear stress, and velocity magnitude) are directly relevant to the COU decision on absolute hemolysis levels. NIH is the regulatory-accepted metric for hemolysis assessment per FDA guidance. Shear stress is the primary mechanical driver of RBC damage in the power-law hemolysis model. Velocity magnitude governs residence time and cumulative damage. All three QoIs are computed and reported at all 5 operating points. Relevance is well-established in the peer-reviewed literature and FDA guidance documents. Achieved Gradation 4 is consistent with the required level; this factor is met.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/qoi-relevance-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: all QoIs must be directly linked to the regulatory acceptance criterion (NIH < 0.05 g/100 L); traceability from each QoI to the clinical harm mechanism must be documented; QoIs must be computed at all COU operating points."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Relevance of validation activities to the COU at MRL 5 requires Gradation 5: validation experiments performed on the actual device geometry under COU-representative conditions including patient-range blood properties. Validation was performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry (identical to COU geometry), which is a strength. However, the operating points used in validation (3 of 5 COU points) do not span the full COU operating envelope; 2 extreme operating points (8 L/min, 4000 RPM and 3 L/min, 2000 RPM) were not included in validation due to experimental constraints. Blood analogue rather than human blood was used as the primary validation fluid, introducing rheological dissimilarity. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects validation on the correct geometry at 3 of 5 operating points with analogue fluid.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/validation-relevance-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: validation experiments at all 5 COU operating points on the actual device geometry; human or porcine blood (not analogue) as primary validation fluid; demonstration that validation conditions bound the COU operating space; documented similarity analysis between validation and COU conditions."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error at MRL 5 requires Gradation 4: iterative convergence demonstrated to machine precision for steady-state solutions, time-step independence study for transient effects, and floating-point round-off error analysis. Residual convergence to 10⁻⁶ was achieved for continuity and momentum equations. However, the hemolysis transport equation residual converged only to 10⁻⁴, which is insufficient for Gradation 4. No time-step independence study was performed for the transient impeller rotation (sliding mesh), and floating-point round-off analysis was not documented. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects demonstrated convergence for primary flow equations with documented residual histories.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/solver-error-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Numerical solver error acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: iterative convergence to 10⁻⁶ or better for all governing equations including hemolysis transport; time-step independence study with ≥3 time steps for transient sliding mesh simulation; documented floating-point round-off error analysis for hemolysis accumulation integration."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Use error assessment at MRL 5 requires Gradation 4: independent analyst replication of all simulation results, documented operator training records, and formal review of all model setup parameters by a qualified independent reviewer. An internal peer review of boundary condition setup was conducted, but replication by an independent analyst was not performed. Operator training records exist for the primary analyst but not for the two supporting engineers who performed mesh generation and post-processing. The hemolysis model coefficient selection was not independently reviewed. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects internal peer review of primary simulation setup without independent replication.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/use-error-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Use error acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: independent analyst replication of all 5 operating point simulations with documented agreement within numerical uncertainty; training records for all personnel performing simulation tasks; independent qualified review of hemolysis model coefficient selection and boundary condition specification."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Model form assessment at MRL 5 requires Gradation 5: systematic evaluation of all model form assumptions with quantified model form uncertainty, including turbulence model selection, hemolysis power-law model form, and non-Newtonian blood rheology model. The k-ω SST turbulence model was selected based on literature precedent for rotating machinery; no alternative turbulence model comparison was performed. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model was used without evaluation of alternative mechanistic models (e.g., Faghih-Sharp). Non-Newtonian rheology was modeled with a Carreau-Yasuda model; sensitivity to rheological model parameters was assessed in Monte Carlo UQ but model form alternatives were not compared. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects documented model form choices with literature justification but without systematic model form uncertainty quantification.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-form-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: comparison of ≥2 turbulence models; comparison of ≥2 hemolysis model forms with quantified model form uncertainty contribution; sensitivity analysis demonstrating relative contribution of each model form assumption to total hemolysis prediction uncertainty; documented justification for final model form selection."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Model inputs assessment at MRL 5 requires Gradation 4: all uncertain model inputs characterized with probability distributions derived from patient population data or in-situ measurements, with full propagation through Monte Carlo UQ. Blood viscosity and density distributions were derived from literature population statistics rather than patient-specific measurements. Hemolysis model coefficients (α, β, C in power-law) were taken from Giersiepen et al. (1990) without updated uncertainty characterization from more recent experimental data. Inlet velocity profile was assumed uniform (plug flow) rather than characterized from measurements. Monte Carlo UQ was performed but with simplified input distributions. Achieved Gradation 3 reflects Monte Carlo UQ with literature-derived input distributions for primary parameters.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-inputs-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: probability distributions for all uncertain inputs derived from in-situ measurements or recent patient population data (post-2010); hemolysis model coefficients characterized from updated experimental dataset; measured inlet velocity profile distribution used as boundary condition uncertainty input; full Monte Carlo propagation with ≥5000 samples."
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test samples as a credibility factor applies to validation experiments using physical test specimens where sample-to-sample variability in material properties or geometry is a source of uncertainty. For the FDA generic centrifugal pump validation, the pump geometry is a fixed computational reference geometry; physical pump specimens were not fabricated for this study. Experimental hemolysis data were obtained from the published FDA benchmark dataset (Stewart et al., 2012) using a single pump specimen per operating condition. Sample-to-sample geometric variability is therefore not an independent source of uncertainty in this validation activity and is scoped out. Geometric uncertainty is instead addressed within the model inputs factor via nominal geometry tolerances."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 4,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters at MRL 5 requires Gradation 4: formal similarity analysis demonstrating that validation experiment input parameters are equivalent to COU input parameters within quantified uncertainty bounds, covering all dimensionless groups relevant to hemolysis (Reynolds number, Kolmogorov length scale, exposure time). A qualitative similarity argument was made that the FDA generic pump geometry and operating conditions approximate VAD COU conditions. However, no formal dimensional analysis was performed. The validation Reynolds numbers (Re 4,200–18,500) partially overlap the COU range (Re 3,800–22,000) but the two extreme COU operating points fall outside the validated range. Blood analogue-to-blood viscosity ratio was not formally characterized as a similarity parameter. Achieved Gradation 2 reflects documented operating condition overlap with qualitative similarity argument only.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/input-equivalency-mrl5",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Input parameter equivalency acceptance criteria for MRL 5",
        "description": "Required: formal dimensional analysis identifying all relevant similarity parameters for hemolysis prediction; quantitative demonstration that validation Re, Kolmogorov scale, and exposure time distributions overlap COU distributions at all 5 operating points; documented blood analogue similarity parameter (viscosity ratio, density ratio) with uncertainty bounds."
      }
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cou2-vad-not-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Not accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU2 (VAD hemolysis prediction, MRL 5, Class III) is Not accepted based on documented shortfalls in 10 of 12 assessed credibility factors. The most consequential gaps are: (1) Test conditions (achieved 3, required 5): validation did not use PIV-measured inlet profiles or full rheological characterization, and 2 of 5 COU operating points were not covered in experiments; (2) Output comparison (achieved 3, required 5): no spatial field validation against PIV data and no formal ASME V&V 20 validation metric computed; (3) Model form (achieved 3, required 5): no turbulence model comparison and no hemolysis model form uncertainty quantification; (4) Equivalency of input parameters (achieved 2, required 4): two COU operating points fall outside the validated Reynolds number range with no formal similarity analysis; (5) Software quality assurance (achieved 2, required 4): custom hemolysis UDF not independently reviewed and regression test coverage insufficient. The Monte Carlo UQ was completed and is noted as a positive element; however, UQ alone cannot compensate for the structural gaps in validation coverage and model form assessment at this risk level. No offset rationale is claimed. The package must be substantially augmented before resubmission: at minimum, PIV-based validation at all 5 operating points, independent code review of hemolysis UDF, turbulence model sensitivity study, and formal ASME V&V 20 validation metric computation are required.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
